        <h2></h2>
        
            <div class="gen-group">
              
              <div class="gen-group__content">
                <p class="subheading">Site managed by</p>
                <h2>Cymric Limited</h2>
              </div>
            </div>
        
        <div class="gen-content">
          <p>Bromfield Sand &amp; Gravel Co. Limited has operated at the heart of the Earl of Plymouth’s Estate in Shropshire since the mid 1960’s. The gravel pit has helped construct the foundations of the community for over 50 years by supplying essential building aggregates to local trades, businesses and domestic customers in the region.</p>
<p>In line with the Estate’s ethos, particular attention has been paid to restore previously quarried land back to productive grazing farmland. Bromfield Sand &amp; Gravel’s sister company Cymric Limited has since taken the opportunity to further enhance this reclaimed land with investment in solar technology, ensuring further productivity from a formerly brownfield site. In an unprecedented decision at the time the planning application for the solar development was approved without a single objection. Planners and local countryside campaigners alike supported the scheme for its community engagement, biodiversity planning and site suitability. </p>
<p>Working towards a more sustainable future, the solar farm became operational in October 2015 and now contributes towards making the sand and gravel business carbon neutral. Cymric is able to deliver surplus energy from the solar site to other businesses on the Estate including Ludlow Food Centre’s 160 seat cafe Ludlow Kitchen and The Clive. This compliments Cymric’s investment in two other renewable energy ventures nearby, namely the hydroelectric schemes <a href="https://piclo.uk/p/cymric-lower-weir/JbgU1">Cymric Lower</a> and <a href="https://piclo.uk/p/cymric-upper-weir/zv9UB">Upper Weir</a>, which also provide clean, renewable energy to local users.</p>
          <p class="read-more"><a href="#" class="button">Read More</a></p>
        </div>
        

